<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
And they all wore cloths of patch work when the stepped onto the quay<br>
A woman and two children boy of six and girl of three…<br>
Her man had died in crossing so she did what woman ought,<br>
Taking laundry, weaving, mending for the men upon the dock.<br>
But the money in our harbor town for doing homely chores <br>
Was not enough to keep her children fed nor in winter keep them warm,<br>
And her man had died in crossing so she did as mothers can<br>
Gave her body to all buyers… never love for any man.<br>
<br>
And they all wore close of patchwork as they went about there days<br>
The children grew like wild flowers under mother’s loving gaze.<br>
She taught them songs and stories of a land so far away<br>
And the boy he played the fiddle like his father used to play.<br>
And with golden hair a flying the girl danced to those old tune<br>
Lilting voice to the heavens flashing feet on coble stone.<br>
But the woman sadly smiling she grew paler by the day.<br>
No one cared or even noticed as her life did slowly wane…<br>
<br>
And she wore a gown of patchwork when they laid her in the grave<br>
No one there to mourn her save to children five and eight.<br>
Left alone to wonder they went from town to town<br>
Flying fingers on a fiddle and a dancing patchwork gown.<br>
Putting out a bowl for coins as they’d seen others do.<br>
She would sing and dance a dervish to her brothers fiddle tune.<br>
But no one barred to ask them of their family or their home.<br>
Each day ended as it started with the two of them alone.<br>
<br>
And they wore a cloths of patchwork as they walked those city streets.<br>
Seasons changed around them winters chill for summers heat.<br>
One winter night near candle mass the two stood on the street<br>
Playing songs for copper pieces to buy the drink and meat.<br>
And as darkness closed around them they peered at windows bright<br>
And to ease the longing in their hearts they played into the night<br>
And the music sounded like angels song the little feet danced on<br>
And the Patchwork Children played that night till finally they were warm.<br>
<br>
And they both wore cloths of patchwork when they found them the next day.<br>
Frozen fingers on a fiddle frozen tears upon there face.<br>
And the people of that quarter spoke of wonders in the night.<br>
Fiery music played by angels heard beneath the pale moonlight.<br>
And as people gathered around them they spoke of a wondrous thing…<br>
Seen amidst those snow drifts it looked like angel wings.<br>
<br>
